You are nowhere near strong enough to be thinking of slam so you bid 4\S.

The contract would be 4\S played by South.

To make North the declarer  ROTATE. 

North plays 4\S. East leads the \CT. West wins the \CA. They continue  \Cs and you ruff the third one in dummy.

Those losers are based on dummy's hand, not yours. You can figure them either way but it is usually easier to determine losers based on the long-trump hand. It's important to remember it in this Deal because the zero losers in \Hs assumes you will ruff a \H in your hand. 

Pull one round of trumps with dummy's \SK. Both defenders follow suit. Play the \HA, then \H6 to dummy's \HK. On this trick East follows with the \HT.  

The Plan is still the same, you will ruff the \H in your hand, but you better be sure to ruff with your \SA. Aha! Your precaution pays off when East shows out of \Hs, but of course he cannot over-ruff your \SA.

When you are ruffing, ruff with as high a trump as you can afford.

Here, with only 2 trumps left out, you can afford the \SA.}
